			Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial
		-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 1
			-
				-
					If the plaintiff summons the defendant to court the defendant shall go. If the
					defendant does not go the plaintiff shall call a witness thereto. Only then the
					plaintiff shall seize the defendant.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 2
			-
				-
					If the defendant attempts evasion or takes flight the plaintiff shall lay hand
					on him.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 3
			-
				-
					If sickness or age is an impediment he who summons the defendant to court shall
					grant him a vehicle. If he a does not wish he shall not spread a carriage with
					cushions.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 4
			-
				-
					For a freeholder' a freeholder shall be surety; for a proletary anyone who
					wishes shall be surety.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 5
			-
				-
					There shall be the same right of bond and of conveyance with the Roman people
					for a steadfast person and for a person restored to allegiance.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 6
			-
				-
					When the parties agree on the matter the magistrate shall announce it.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 7
			-
				-
					If they agree not on terms the parties shall state their case before the
					assembly in the meeting place or before the magistrate in the market place
					before noon. Both parties being present shall plead the case throughout
					together.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 8
			-
				-
					If one of the parties does not appear the magistrate shall adjudge the case,
					after noon, in favor of the one present.
				-
			-
				Table 1 - Proceedings Preliminary to Trial: Law 9
			-
				-
					If both parties are present sunset shall be the time limit of the proceedings.
